SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 1113
By Southerland
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend the Foster Grandparent
Program of Greene County on the occasion of
its sixtieth anniversary.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should recognize
those programs and organizations that have demonstrated a sustained commitment to
strengthening communities and improving the lives of Tennessee citizens; and
WHEREAS, the Foster Grandparent Program of Greene County is celebrating its sixtieth
anniversary, marking six decades of dedicated service to children and families in the region; and
WHEREAS, the Foster Grandparent Program provides older adults with meaningful
opportunities to serve as volunteer mentors to children in schools and after-school programs,
fostering intergenerational connections that benefit both participants; and
WHEREAS, through their service, foster grandparents devote significant time and care
to helping young people build self-confidence, achieve personal independence, and overcome
challenges, thereby supporting their development into productive members of society; and
WHEREAS, the program establishes clear standards for participation, including age,
residency, income eligibility, and background screening, ensuring that volunteers are well-suited
to serve in these important roles; and
WHEREAS, in addition to the personal rewards of service, foster grandparents receive
training, support, and modest stipends, enabling them to continue their contributions while
maintaining their own well-being; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should specially recognize the Foster Grandparent
Program of Greene County and applaud its enduring impact on children and families; now,
therefore,
SJR1113
017550
- 1 -

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we commend the Foster Grandparent Program of
Greene County on the occasion of its sixtieth anniversary, honoring its legacy of service and its
ongoing contributions to the well-being of children and families in Tennessee.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
